   <a class="perm" href="https://solomons-says.com/post/188397960040/aim">&nbsp;</a>
   <div class="post">

      <h2>A.I.M.</h2>
      <p>2013 MacArthur Grant winner Kyle Abraham can afford to take risks, as his current season at the Joyce Theater proves. Of the six dances on the program two, are made by other dance makers than Abraham. The opener, &ldquo;Big Rings,&rdquo; is by his company member, Keerati Jinakunwiphat, and the other is by Trisha Brown, a &ldquo;genius award&rdquo; grantee of an earlier era. The season, which runs October 15-20, is selling like hotcakes, also because of another feature, two performances of a solo Abraham created for American Ballet Theater star Misty Copeland.<br /></p><p>Jinakunwiphat&rsquo;s dance for a team of three women and three men, wearing custom sweat suits by Karen Young, each emblazoned with their real surnames on the back, uses a collage of music that ranges from from Yoyo Ma, playing Camille Saint Saens&rsquo;s &ldquo;The Dying Swan,&rdquo; to rappers Alan Parsons Project, Quad City DJs, and Chance the Rapper, into a score arranged by Zach Berns. The choreographer&rsquo;s sensibility is hip-hop, and the versatile dancers (Tamisha Guy, Claude &ldquo;CJ&rdquo; Johnson, Javon Jones, Catherine Ellis Kirk, Marcella Lewis, and Jae Neal) are adept in street style, which Abraham often references in his own dances. </p><figure class="tmblr-full" data-orig-height="2000" data-orig-width="3000" style=""><img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/5a5dbda5164d94a7ca95d7448cb71072/09995e86277dae56-8b/s500x750/1cb42116dfc0250e97cd9f911b3af142f32e7b9b.jpg" data-orig-height="2000" data-orig-width="3000" width="500" height="333" alt="image" /></figure><p><i>A.I.M. artists in Keerati Jinakunwiphat&rsquo;s BIG RINGS. (l-r): Jae Nea, Catherine Ellis Kirk, Tamisha Guy (lifted), Claude&nbsp;&ldquo;CJ&rdquo; Johnson, Javon Jones, and Marcella Lewis.&nbsp;photo by Christopher Duggan</i></p><p>Dan Scully&rsquo;s lighting, here and throughout the program, deftly enhances the choreography with quick, dramatic shifts from silhouette to hard side light to pools that pinpoint dancers, timed musically. The lighting, in fact, adds a dynamic finish to &ldquo;Rings&rdquo; by flashing brightly on a lineup of the cast before blacking out; the ending delightfully catches us by surprise. </p><figure class="tmblr-full" data-orig-height="3630" data-orig-width="4538" style=""><img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/72003b2944100e919df61f7e93d1b436/09995e86277dae56-38/s500x750/0ef161c309d9e43a2e8eacda68cdf8316b34957b.jpg" data-orig-height="3630" data-orig-width="4538" width="500" height="400" alt="image" /></figure><p><i>A.I.M. dancer Marcella Lewis in Kyle Abraham&rsquo;s SHOW PONY.&nbsp;photo by Sharen Bradford</i></p><p>&ldquo;Show Pony&rdquo; is a solo from 2018 performed. On opening night by Marcella Lewis (alternating with Guy in subsequent performances) in a shiny gold body suit by Fritz Masten adds pizzazz. The brief solo to the percussive score &ldquo;Hatshepsut&rdquo; by Jiin is a vivid example of Abraham&rsquo;s unique style of liquid, angularity, unexpected energy shifts, and cannily unpredictable spatial shifts. The dance is over quick as a liquor shot, leaving you agape at its dynamic momentum.</p><figure class="tmblr-full" data-orig-height="2333" data-orig-width="3500" style=""><img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/16e0aa86e63f9bac136c6e1732b2124e/09995e86277dae56-08/s500x750/fd4d65ed096ca5e08e7e79932bfb781f7c0482b6.jpg" data-orig-height="2333" data-orig-width="3500" width="500" height="333" alt="image" /></figure><p><i><i>A.I.M.&lsquo;s&nbsp;Marcella Lewis in Kyle Abraham&rsquo;s SHOW PONY. photo by Sharen Bradford</i></i></p><p>Next, in the recent development of prestigious modern companies&rsquo; presenting revivals of classic modern masterworks by others &ndash; Stephen Petronio&rsquo;s Bloodlines Project with works by Merce Cunningham and by his mentor Trisha Brown, for example, and Paul Taylor&rsquo;s American Modern American Dance initiative and rebranding to commission other choreographers &ndash; here, A.I.M. dances Brown&rsquo;s 1976 piece &ldquo;Solo Olos.&rdquo; The opening night cast (Johnson, Jones, Kirk, Donovan Reed, and Jada Jenai Williams) in white pajamas captures Brown&rsquo;s signature laid-back, momentum-based motion, letting body parts go wherever physical impulses send them. They do a repeating phrase with dancers, by turns, changing their location ns within the formations. It&rsquo;s been restaged by Brown company members Cecily Campbell and Stuart Shugg, whose meticulous coaching the dancers have organically absorbed. </p><figure class="tmblr-full" data-orig-height="3840" data-orig-width="5760" style=""><img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/c88f69cc679e49462f4f7ff57c2b77cb/09995e86277dae56-1a/s500x750/ffbd96f7ca37913f4c76d34dd695b18e7f3f13f6.jpg" data-orig-height="3840" data-orig-width="5760" width="500" height="333" alt="image" /></figure><p><i>A.I.M. (l-r): <i>CJ Johnson and Catherine Ellis Kirk. </i>in Trisha Brown&rsquo;s SOLO OLOS. photo by Stephen Schreiber</i></p><p>Early on, Reed hops off the stage, takes a seat in the front row, grabs a mic, and begins giving the dancers instructions that interrupt and reconfigure the ongoing phrase &ndash; &nbsp;&ldquo;Jada, reverse!&rdquo;; &ldquo;Javon, branch!&rdquo;; Katherine and CJ, spill!&rdquo;; etc. The commands seamlessly shift the dancers into and out of unisons with partners in this good-natured game, which ends abruptly with a blackout, when Reed states matter-of-factly, &ldquo;We&rsquo;ll be going on&hellip;&rdquo; </p><figure class="tmblr-full" data-orig-height="2333" data-orig-width="3500" style=""><img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/f60a3ee352081109ef01223c070e1f8b/09995e86277dae56-db/s500x750/c78e455580770b79e3d916211060b2e12206e193.jpg" data-orig-height="2333" data-orig-width="3500" width="500" height="333" alt="image" /></figure><p><i>A.I.M. director Kyle Abraham in his COCOON. </i>&nbsp;<i>photo by Stephen Schreiber</i></p><p>Abraham finally appears after intermission with the world premiere of &ldquo;Cocoon&rdquo; to Bj&ouml;rk music, sung a cappella, in a live arrangement by lead vocalist Nicholas Ryan Gant , backed by a chorus of eight. Wearing a multicolored, moth-like jumpsuit by Giles Deacon, Abraham emerges, Butoh-slow, from a kneeling crouch on the floor upstage and moves glacially on the ground, throughout the first section. </p><figure class="tmblr-full" data-orig-height="3000" data-orig-width="2000" style=""><img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/521da4ed541286079c81c314ad62c34b/09995e86277dae56-70/s500x750/0190d939ec926d3efa4366587775831efa6e1e26.jpg" data-orig-height="3000" data-orig-width="2000" width="500" height="750" alt="image" /></figure><p><i><i>A.I.M. director Kyle Abraham in his COCOON.</i>photo by Christopher Duggan</i></p><p>When he rises, his movement remains measured with occasional abrupt bodily twitches and rippling arms. His demeanor is calm and assured without pyrotechnics. As the last line of the song repeats, &ldquo;You&rsquo;ll be given love,&rdquo; he stands motionless, gazing offstage, while lights gradually fade. &nbsp;</p><figure class="tmblr-full" data-orig-height="2333" data-orig-width="3500" style=""><img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/52732cd1ced623df747794c5431c6ec1/09995e86277dae56-b4/s500x750/1d22e9eca1760a4622954856029313b1e48416db.jpg" data-orig-height="2333" data-orig-width="3500" width="500" height="333" alt="image" /></figure><p><i>A.I.M. in Kyle Abraham&rsquo;s STUDIES ON A FAREWELL. (l-r): Tamisha Guy, Jada Jenai Williams, Claude &ldquo;CJ&rdquo; Johnson.&nbsp;photo by Stephen Schreiber</i></p><p>&ldquo;Studies on a Farewell,&rdquo; also a premiere and commissioned by the Joyce Theater Foundation, uses the music &ldquo;Four Studies&rdquo; by Nico Muhly, a piece for two live violinists (Katherine Liccardo and Chelsea Starbuck Smith) over an electronic track. In the dance for nine, dressed in silky, fitted pajamas in tan and brown tones that match the dancers&rsquo; complexions (again by Masten), couples continuously form and dissolve in thoughtfully designed spatial patterns that remain, restless, continuously transforming and tinged with sadness &ndash; or perhaps acceptance. The dance represents the work of a maturing artist, who&rsquo;s confident enough to move beyond virtuosity and who dares to engage our thought and feeling.</p><figure class="tmblr-full" data-orig-height="2333" data-orig-width="3500" style=""><img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/5916eea7c0b3f2621e568fe7a115366b/09995e86277dae56-98/s500x750/4dc57b311aac988028cdafd615b6237874e35cb6.jpg" data-orig-height="2333" data-orig-width="3500" width="500" height="333" alt="image" /></figure><p><i><i>A.I.M. in Kyle Abraham&rsquo;s STUDIES ON A FAREWELL. (l-r): Catherine Ellis Kirk,&nbsp;</i>&nbsp;Donovan Reed, Claude &ldquo;CJ&rdquo; Johnson, and Keerati Jinakunwiphat. photo by Stephen Schreiber</i></p><figure class="tmblr-full" data-orig-height="3000" data-orig-width="2000" style=""><img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/46e3af93cd500577da236bf2dec893c5/09995e86277dae56-b0/s500x750/f8b9a76be181448f5d8107d5f78ebb683c080199.jpg" data-orig-height="3000" data-orig-width="2000" width="500" height="750" alt="image" /></figure><p><i>A.I.M. Misty Copeland in ASH by Kyle Abraham&nbsp;with her collaboration.&nbsp;photo by Christopher Duggan</i></p><p>The program closes with another unconventional choice &ndash; &ldquo;Ash,&rdquo; a solo Abraham created this year for and in collaboration with Misty Copeland. Highlighted by Scully&rsquo;s cool, kinetic lighting, on a mysterious, shadowy stage, Copeland begins upstage, moving like a delicate, nocturnal creature &ndash; a moth, a bird, a firefly &ndash; discovering her own materiality, pulling a shoulder, extending her limbs into the dim space around her, tentatively venturing to new locations along diagonal paths in search of something ineffable. She rises to balance on her pointes, fans a leg in a sweeping arc or into a startlingly high extension; she turns with an exquisitely arced rear leg; she darts diagonally here and there with elbows crooked to the sides, clearing her way with toes jutting in front of her.</p><figure class="tmblr-full" data-orig-height="3000" data-orig-width="2000" style=""><img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/14625cabd6fab906a3ed190d514bb236/09995e86277dae56-d0/s500x750/e595ecb82960cff37302ec303156ae274869b038.jpg" data-orig-height="3000" data-orig-width="2000" width="500" height="750" alt="image" /></figure><p><i><i>A.I.M. Misty Copeland in ASH, by Kyle Abraham with her collaboration. photo by Christopher Duggan</i></i></p><p>Copeland&rsquo;s artistry makes every detail crystal clear, and Abraham&rsquo;s movement adds his own personal attitude to her flawless classicism. In a slow, backwards walk towards the audience, Copeland&rsquo;s outstretched arms and hands subtly waving, &ldquo;Come on!&rdquo; with the implied challenge of a Black sister, affirms that, &ldquo;Yeah, this, too, is a part of who I can be!&rdquo; before retreating backwards into darkness doing little ballet coup&eacute;s. The effusive hug between choreographer and dancer at curtain call signals that this collaboration may have other chapters yet to come.</p><p><i> </i></p><p><i>Gus Solomons jr, &copy; 2019</i></p>








